I've identified the issue with your Todo app where items don't appear immediately after adding them. This is a classic case of a mismatch between client-side and server-side behavior.

## The Root Cause

The problem is in how the application handles form submissions and page refreshes:

1. **Server-Side Rendering with Page Redirects**: In `app.js`, when you add a new todo item, the server adds it to the in-memory array and then redirects:
   ```javascript
   app.post('/todos', (req, res) => {
     const newTodo = {
       id: Date.now(),
       text: req.body.todoText,
       completed: false
     };
     todos.push(newTodo);
     res.redirect('/');
   });
   ```

2. **Client-Side JavaScript Conflict**: In `public/js/app.js`, there's client-side JavaScript that's set up to handle toggle and delete actions via AJAX, but it doesn't properly handle the add action:
   ```javascript
   // Let the form submit normally for adding new todos
   // The server will handle the redirect back to the updated page
   ```

3. **Browser Caching**: The browser is likely caching the response from the server, causing the page to show stale data after the redirect.

## The Solution

Here are two approaches to fix this issue:

### Option 1: Make the Add Action Use AJAX (Recommended)

Update the client-side JavaScript to handle the form submission via AJAX, similar to how toggle and delete are handled:

```javascript
// Add this to your public/js/app.js file
todoForm.addEventListener('submit', function(e) {
  e.preventDefault();

  const todoText = todoInput.value.trim();
  if (!todoText) return;

  fetch('/todos', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'application/json',
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({ todoText })
  })
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => {
    if (data.todo) {
      // Remove empty state if it exists
      const emptyState = todoList.querySelector('.empty-state');
      if (emptyState) {
        emptyState.remove();
      }

      // Create new todo item
      const todoItem = document.createElement('li');
      todoItem.className = 'todo-item';
      todoItem.innerHTML = `
        <span class="todo-text">${data.todo.text}</span>
        <div class="todo-actions">
          <form action="/todos/${data.todo.id}/toggle" method="POST" class="inline-form">
            <button type="submit" class="btn-toggle"></button>
          </form>
          <form action="/todos/${data.todo.id}/delete" method="POST" class="inline-form">
            <button type="submit" class="btn-delete"></button>
          </form>
        </div>
      `;

      todoList.appendChild(todoItem);
      todoInput.value = '';
    }
  })
  .catch(error => {
    console.error('Error:', error);
  });
});
```

And update the server-side route to return JSON instead of redirecting:

```javascript
app.post('/todos', (req, res) => {
  const newTodo = {
    id: Date.now(),
    text: req.body.todoText,
    completed: false
  };

  todos.push(newTodo);

  // Return the new todo as JSON instead of redirecting
  res.json({ success: true, todo: newTodo });
});
```

### Option 2: Add Cache Control Headers

If you prefer to keep the current redirect approach, add cache control headers to prevent browser caching:

```javascript
// Add this middleware at the top of your app.js
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.set('Cache-Control', 'no-store');
  next();
});
```

## Implementation Plan

1. **Update the server-side code** in `app.js` to handle JSON requests and responses
2. **Update the client-side code** in `public/js/app.js` to use AJAX for adding todos
3. **Test the application** to ensure todos appear immediately after adding

